WAL - Write-Ahead Logging 

What is WAL?
WAL is like keeping a diary of all changes before actually making them.

Key Idea:

First write changes to a log file
Then apply changes to the main database
If crash happens, replay the log to recover

Real benefit: Zero data loss even if system crashes at the worst moment.

Why WAL Matters - Failure Scenario

Without WAL:
You type paragraph 1 and 2
Power fails
You reopen document → Only paragraph 1 exists

With WAL:

You log "Add paragraph 1" then apply
You log "Add paragraph 2" then apply

Power fails

Recovery reads log and replays both changes
You reopen → Both paragraphs exist

How etcd Uses WAL in Kubernetes
When API server receives kubectl create pod:

WAL entry is written: PUT /registry/pods/default/nginx with pod spec
After log is safely written, etcd applies change to main database

Real benefit: Kubernetes control plane can crash during deployment and recover exactly to the same state.

WAL File Structure Example
A typical WAL log file contains entries like:

Entry	Transaction ID	Operation	Key	Value
1	    101	PUT	        /key1	    value1
2	    102	DELETE	    /key2	    -
3	    103	PUT	        /key3	    value3

The Tradeoff - Safety vs Speed
Advantage	                            Disadvantage
Guaranteed recovery after crashes	    Extra disk writes, slower performance
Atomic operations, all or nothing	    Needs disk sync (fsync)
Consistent database state	            Log management overhead


Real World Analogies

Chess Game

WAL = Writing down moves before making them
Crash = Someone bumps the table
Recovery = Replay moves from your notes

Bank Transactions

WAL = Transaction ledger
Crash = Teller computer dies
Recovery = Rebuild accounts from ledger

Performance Optimization Tricks

Modern systems use:

Group commits - Batch multiple writes together
SSD storage - Much faster than HDDs

Parallel log writing

WAL in Action - etcd Example
View etcd WAL files on control plane node:
ls /var/lib/etcd/member/wal/

Output shows .wal files with sequence numbers.

When WAL Saves Your Cluster

Scenario: Kubernetes control plane crashes during a deployment.

On restart:

etcd checks WAL files
Replays unfinished operations
Cluster returns to exact pre-crash state

Real benefit: No manual recovery needed. No data corruption. Cluster resumes exactly where it left off.


Quick Summary
Term	Meaning
WAL 	Write log first, then database
fsync	Force log to disk immediately
Replay	Apply log entries after crash
Commit	When change is permanently saved